<!-- begin paragraph -->
<tr>
<td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
<!-- Add marginal notes below -->
<i>
Skewness and Kurtosis
</i>
</td>
<td width=3D"85%">
<!-- Add main text below -->
A fundamental task in many statistical analyses is to characterize
the <a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section3/eda351=
.htm"><i>location</i></a> and
<a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section3/eda356.htm=
"><i>variability</i></a> of a data set.
A further characterization of the data includes skewness and kurtosis.
<p>
Skewness is a measure of symmetry, or more precisely, the lack of
symmetry.  A distribution, or data set, is symmetric if it looks the
same to the left and right of the center point.
</p><p>
<!-- 2016/02: Re-word following section based on suggestion
     from Peter Westfall
Kurtosis is a measure of whether the data are peaked or flat relative
to a normal distribution.  That is, data sets with high kurtosis
tend to have a distinct peak near the mean, decline rather rapidly,
and have heavy tails.  Data sets with low kurtosis tend to have
a flat top near the mean rather than a sharp peak.  A uniform
distribution would be the extreme case.
-->
Kurtosis is a measure of whether the data are heavy-tailed or
light-tailed relative to a normal distribution. That is, data sets
with high kurtosis tend to have heavy tails, or outliers. Data sets
with low kurtosis tend to have light tails, or lack of outliers. A
uniform distribution would be the extreme case.
</p><p>
The <a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section3/histog=
ra.htm">histogram</a> is an effective graphical
technique for showing both the skewness and kurtosis of data set.
</p></td>
</tr>
<!-- end paragraph -->

